{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b6164b94-176f-4b67-846d-f7c6ad6b5369","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01BcLUUzwGBCurhmwRg5mmu9","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01URaUUR6WhpSDecVxCKwWUL","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDKs","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDKs"}],"interactionId":"dfb60e5d-7b97-4f93-8584-8ba2e687ac36","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names using built-in System.Text.Json functionality.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Before that, the default behavior of System.Text.Json was to use the property names as-is (which for C# properties are typically PascalCase already). But here, the record has lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), which means the generated properties will be `name` and `age` (lowercase) in the positional record syntax.\n \nFor positional records like `public record Person(string name, int age)`, the compiler generates properties matching the parameter casing, so they'd be lowercase. Since .NET 9, `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` converts property names to PascalCase during serialization, which should handle this perfectly in .NET 11.\n\nLet me set up a console app targeting net11.0 and use `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` in the serializer options.","outputTokens":693,"requestId":"EBC9:3A9E72:BB8B08:DBE841:69FE8588"},"id":"8de020ea-5232-4993-b467-027057f0bbb8","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:53:42.492Z","parentId":"9ee32a39-5d55-4e70-8a54-4a4433ac803f"}
